text: A better DEATH WISH movie would have recontextualized the original story around current events by portraying Kersey as a pacifistic, liberal white man turned cold vigilante killer of mostly black criminals. While Kersey privately considers his actions to be of a MORAL character, show BLM protesters frame his actions as inherently RACIAL in character. Portray the national media as being  disinterested in the killings of black gang members and/or aiding the protesters. Have a police commissioner genuinely interested in arresting Kersey [while building an inaccurate suspect profile] being occasionally obstructed by a police force that mostly identifies with the killer. Make the movie about collective cognitive dissonance and competing narratives struggling to define the social and historical nature of current events [Kersey's fictionalized vigilantism] with each side falsely caricaturing what they each oppose and have projected onto it.  It would make the city streets of Detroit feel increasingly claustrophobic leading to a Wild Bunch standoff/chase sequence between Kersey, street gangs, protesters, and police in the climax.  Instead, we're getting generic action escapism that will leave your mind the second you walk out of the theatre.

text: This could be an interesting remake, but it is going to lack the dark, moody atmosphere of the original. Charles Bronson's performance is subdued, but menacing.  He epitomizes an ordinary person pushed to the edge and decides he would do something about it.  He's believable as Mr. everyperson learning to shoot a gun and putting himself in situations where he would be mugged or attacked so he can get his revenge on all low-life criminals.  For its time, the movie created talk of whether it is moral or immoral for a person to take the law in his own hands.  And Herbie Hancock's jazzy score is an additional highlight.  This new remake looks more like an action movie, like a cross between Die Hard and Taken.

text: All I can say is GUILTY PLEASURE. This film is simply incredible. Both stupidly ridiculous and serious drama it just mixes way too much genres to work. Literally you've seen this type of story million times before , but somehow with addition of paycheck version of Bruce Willis and really dark humour it does provide solid entertainment. You could practically call this a CONTRIVANCES : THE MOVIE because nothing is spontaneous here and you can guess everything that happens like you personally have written the script. It is self aware in a way and definitely a beer and pizza picture, but other than that don't go in expecting anything masterfully crafted and though provoking because this is turn your brain off experience. 2.5/5

text: I know it's not official, but I will always consider this movie a prelude to Die Hard even if Willis is 65 years old. It has all the characteristics...daughter's name is Lucy (cmon), "John" learns how to shoot, he takes matters into his own hands since he doesn't want to wait for the cops, and perhaps gives him a reason to join the law enforcement as a detective since he enjoys finding out about the small details. In my mind, "John" is still a young adult in this movie, and this is the making of the badassery in Die Hard.
